{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17632406","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17632406"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T17:43:23+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T17:43:23+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17433"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17433","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17433"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.12,0.81,0.04,0.04,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10123"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70789"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10123","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10123"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17433"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56255"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"5326"},{"type":"tags","id":"5475"},{"type":"tags","id":"11724"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23723"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23802"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70789","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/70789"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EIn epidemiological research, different study designs are used to investigate associations between exposures and health outcomes.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the key characteristic of a cohort study?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Randomly allocates participants to different exposures","Follows groups forward in time based on exposure status","Examines trends in disease occurrence over decades","Compares cases and controls at a single point in time","Measures all variables simultaneously in a population"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe defining characteristic of a cohort study is that it \u003Cstrong\u003Efollows groups forward in time based on exposure status\u003C/strong\u003E to observe the development of outcomes. This allows researchers to calculate incidence rates and establish temporal relationships between exposures and outcomes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERandomly allocates participants to different exposures\u003C/strong\u003E describes a randomised controlled trial, where researchers actively assign participants to intervention groups.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EExamines trends in disease occurrence over decades\u003C/strong\u003E describes an ecological or time trend study, which looks at population-level patterns rather than individual exposures.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECompares cases and controls at a single point in time\u003C/strong\u003E describes a case-control study, which retrospectively examines exposures in people with and without a disease.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMeasures all variables simultaneously in a population\u003C/strong\u003E describes a cross-sectional study, which captures exposure and outcome data at the same time point.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECohort studies are particularly valuable for studying multiple outcomes from a single exposure and for calculating absolute risks. However, they can be time-consuming and expensive, particularly for rare outcomes or those with long latency periods.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["A cohort study follows groups of people over time to examine the relationship between exposure and outcome.","Cohort studies can be prospective (following groups forward in time) or retrospective (looking back at historical data).","Cohort studies are useful for calculating incidence rates and relative risks."],"references":["Shultz JM, Sullivan LM, Galea S. Public Health: An Introduction to the Science and Practice of Population Health. Springer Publishing Company; 2021."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56255"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17433"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56255","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/56255"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-16T14:03:24+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-16T14:04:30+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10123"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70789"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"5326","links":{"self":"https://app.emed